{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603735"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:42:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:42:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.22,0.14,0.47,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71385"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8468"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7065"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20368"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71385"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe prostate gland has distinct anatomical zones with different clinical significance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about prostatic anatomy is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The central zone comprises 50% of prostate volume","The peripheral zone is the main site of benign prostatic hyperplasia","The transition zone is the most common site of prostate cancer","The central zone surrounds the prostatic urethra","The prostatic utricle derives from the paramesonephric duct"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral zone\u003C/strong\u003E actually comprises about 25% of the glandular prostate volume, not 50%. It surrounds the ejaculatory ducts as they pass through the prostate. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eperipheral zone\u003C/strong\u003E makes up about 70% of the prostate gland and is where the majority of prostate cancers develop, while benign prostatic hyperplasia mostly happens in the transition zone. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etransition zone\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for about 5% of prostate volume in young men and is located around the proximal urethra - it is not the primary site of prostate cancer. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral zone\u003C/strong\u003E has a relationship with the ejaculatory ducts rather than the urethra.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostatic utricle\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the paramesonephric (M\u00fcllerian) duct system during embryological development. This structure can be found in the prostatic urethra at the verumontanum, positioned between the openings of the ejaculatory ducts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The peripheral zone comprises 70% of the prostate gland and is the most common site of prostate cancer","The transition zone surrounds the prostatic urethra and is the main site of benign prostatic hyperplasia","The prostatic utricle is derived from the M\u00fcllerian (paramesonephric) duct"],"references":["Zynger, D. L., Zynger, D., Parwani, A. V., \u0026 Parwani, A. (2014). Prostate pathology. Demos Medical Publishing.","Aaron L, Franco OE, Hayward SW. Review of Prostate Anatomy and Embryology and the Etiology of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia. Urol Clin North Am. 2016 Aug;43(3):279-88. doi: 10.1016/j.ucl.2016.04.012. PMID: 27476121; PMCID: PMC4968575.","Singh O, Bolla SR. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Prostate. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK540987/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media.","Ng M, Leslie SW, Baradhi KM. Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia. [Updated 2024 Oct 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558920/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T11:35:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T11:35:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8468"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71385"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonym